CELINA PRIMARY SCHOOL
Teacher Assistant's and Aide

Celina Primary School posted a job.
September 1 at 8:07 AM ¬∑

Celina Primary School is looking for help! We have the following positions open:

Teacher Assistant 8:30-2:45 daily. This person would assist in classrooms, on the playground, and in the cafeteria.

Teacher Assistant 9:30-3:45 daily. This person would assist in classrooms, on the playground, and in the cafeteria.

Educational Aide: 10:45-1:15 daily. This person would help on the playground.

If interested in any of these positions, please contact Michelle Duncan, Principal at 419-586-8300 ext. 2500 as soon as possible.

All applicants should submit application and/or letter of interest to the Superintendent's Office/Central Office at the Education Complex, 585 E. Livingston Street, Celina, Ohio.

*Resumes submitted online through this posting may not be received or reviewed. All resumes should be submitted in person at the Superintendent's Office/Central Office as listed above.

Celina Intermediate School
August 8 at 8:53 AM ¬∑

CIS FAMILIES,
If any of you are out and about this TAX FREE weekend and are purchasing your school supplies, Mrs. Sudhoff would be forever grateful if you picked up an extra plastic pencil box (5x8‚Äù size). Due to the changes with reopening schools, our art supplies will be kept in individual boxes for each student. This means each student will need an extra 5x8‚Äù PLASTIC pencil box for art class, which will hold their own individual supplies. This was not on the supply list, as no one knew what the guidelines would be for schools reopening.

If you would like to donate extra pencil boxes, they would be accepted with open arms, as well.

We would also be extremely thankful if anyone would like to donate 18-gallon storage totes to keep the pencil boxes for each homeroom separated!

Please email Mrs. Sudhoff with any questions at amanda.sudhoff@celinaschools.org

THANK YOU!

post_text:
The Celina Boys Basketball program will be hosting a youth camp on August 10-12 at the Celina Feildhouse. The camp will be for those boys entering grades 4-6 for the 2020-2021 school year. The goal for the camp is promote the fundamental skills necessary for basketball players to succeed on the court and provide them with skills that can be improved upon at home.

There are two ways to register for camp. One option is the paper form shown below. The second option is to fill out the Google Form, which the link is included in the post. In either case, the deadline for registration is August 6, 2020. Any registration received after that date will be assessed a $5 late fee for the shirt order. Paper copies of the form will be available at the Shell Station next to Happy Dayz and the High School office starting Monday, July 27, 2020. #CHSBasketball üèÄ

If you have any questions or concerns, please contact Coach Johns at adam.johns@celinaschools.org

Form Link: https://forms.gle/j2qPLS525rtL9XV89

We wish a happy retirement to Mrs. Moeller! She was first hired to work High School Intervention with Jo Muether. She then moved to 5th and 6th grade Intervention and did that for many years at CIS. The last several years she taught 6th grade Reading and Writing. She said she loved every minute of it! She loved seeing the eyes of the students when they learned something and then were able to apply it on their own!!!
CIS and CCS wish Mrs. Moeller the best in her retirement! #CelinaNowBulldogForever #DoMore

post_text: Mrs. Barbara Decker has taught for 35 years! During her 31 years with Celina City Schools she taught at Franklin, Primary, Elementary and Celina Intermediate. She was devoted to bringing out the best in each of her students and encouraged them to be the best of their ability. She volunteered as caretaker of the Land Lab for several years at CIS and earned the nickname of "Garden Dr". For several years, she was the Word Wizard: teaching root words to students to extend their vocabulary, defining and spelling words in a fun way! During retirement she plans to complete children's books and poetry. Best of wishes to you during your retirement, Mrs. Decker! We wish you only the best! #CelinaNowBulldogForever #DoMore

Celina Middle School is at Celina Middle School.
July 11 at 10:38 AM ¬∑ Celina, OH ¬∑

Today until 2pm is the Ann Esselstein Scholarship fundraising efforts at Celina Middle School. To honor our former Leader and Principal, we have an ongoing scholarship set up in her name through the Civic Foundation. Two scholarships will be given each year, one to a Celina graduate and one to a Parkway graduate. Please help us earn money to make this happen!
An anonymous local nursery has donated Annabelle hydrangeas to help us reach our goal of $10,000. (These plants typically go for $35-$40.) Please join us in honoring Mrs. Esselstein and supporting this Scholarahip. #DoWhatsExpected #AndThenDoSomeMore #CelinaNowBulldogForever #CelinaMiddleSchool

Tri Star Career Compact
July 1 at 12:34 PM ¬∑

Mercer Savings Bank Donates to Tri Star
Mercer Savings Bank has always been deeply rooted in the communities it serves and, as part of that, believes that reinvesting in those communities should be a large part of its mission. Building on that idea, each month one branch is selected to donate $1,000 to an organization of their choice.

Tri Star Career Compact would like to thank Mercer Savings Bank for their generosity. Tri Star staff members Jerry Kohnen and Keith Westrick were 3D printing face shield headbands for local healthcare workers. Pictured for the donation is L-R Brian Stetler, Rick Ross, William Martin, and Tim Buschur.

Attention all upcoming 7th and 8th grade girls interested in playing volleyball in fall...
Open gyms/practices will be every Monday and Thursday from 11-1 at CIS starting June 8th....Starting July 6th open gyms/practices will be every Monday and Thursday from 11-1 in July at CMS. Every athlete must have a physical before Aug 1st -----The school will NOT provide Free physicals this year you must call your physician to make an appointment...
The form will be available on Final Forms on June 11th----please bring it to your Dr appointment....
Please bring a water bottle because water fountain cannot be used...

Questions please call:
Head Coach Angela Bourne 2603161111
Coach Phil Bange 6147061222
8th grade Coach Jill Ballard 9374142570

Andy Mikesell

post_text:
Celina Intermediate School Principal Mr. Derek Wenning presents the CIS 6th Grade Awards for the 2019-2020 school year. #CelinaNowBulldogForever #DoMore #MrDerekWenning #6thGradeAwards

Citizenship Award - This award honors any student who has shown by their words and actions that they possess the qualities and characteristics we hope to instill in all our students.

Outstanding Bulldog Award - This award honors students who do things ‚ÄúThe Bulldog Way‚Äù - A model for excellence, ethics and pride within the classroom.

President's Award for Educational Excellence - Recognizes a student's academic success in the classroom.

The President's Award for Educational Achievement - Recognizes students who show outstanding educational growth, improvement, commitment to or intellectual development in their academic subjects - but do not meet the criteria for the President's Award for Educational Excellence.

From Celina City Schools:
PUBLIC NOTICE
(R.C. 3313.11)
Notice is hereby given, that due to the resignation of one of its Board Members, there is now a vacancy on the Celina City Board of Education, and said Board is seeking qualified and interested candidates to fill said vacancy.
Applicants for this Board position should submit a notice of interest along with their resume outlining their qualifications to Superintendent, Dr. Ken Schmiesing by 4:00 PM on Thursday, May 28, 2020.

Celina Primary School
May 17 at 12:00 PM ¬∑

"Start where you are. Use what you have. Do what you can." ~ Arthur Ashe

Congratulations to the CHS Class of 2020. It seems like just yesterday you were in kindergarten. There have been ups and there have been downs, but you have persevered! This year didn't end the way we thought it might.. we didn't see this coming.

We are so proud of each and everyone of you! We will continue to watch you in the future! Go out and change the world!!!

Take a walk down memory lane! Love, Celina Primary School

Mr. Cory Ahrens is the CES Principal and we salute him on #NationalPrincipalsDay. He has served the Celina City Schools district for the past 7 years. Mr. Ahrens is a super motivator! His positive attitude and generous outpouring of sincere compliments keeps everyone energized and provides the leadership for the outstanding team at CES! Some interesting faces about Mr. Ahrens.....
- He loves the New Orleans Saints and the Cincinnati Reds
- Hobbies include Camping and Cooking/Smoking Meats
- Loves Swedish fish
- Hates peanut butter
- Graduated from Toledo University
- Loves to experiment

post_text:
On #NationalPrincipalsDay, we salute Mr. Phil Metz, CHS Principal. He has served as an administrator in the Celina City Schools district for the past 11 years. Mr. Metz is so knowledgeable! He has a special place in his heart for all students and loves to see them find success. Here are a few special facts about Mr. Metz:
- He enjoys riding his yellow Harley Davidson
- Favorite food is carrots and celery
- One of his "pet peeves" is people talking with their mouth full
- A hobby of his is woodworking
- He likes to boat and travel
- He does not like the beach
- He is an Army Veteran
Thank you for your leadership, Mr. Metz! #CelinaNowBulldogForever #MrPhilMetz

post_text: Today on #NationalPrincipalsDay we recognize our newest district's newest Principal, Mr. Andy Mikesell. He was officially hired less than 2 weeks ago; however, he had been the interim Principal and Assistant Principal at CMS. Before he became the Principal, Mr. Mikesell has served as a HS teacher and for the past several years, the CMS Dean of Students, and has also been the Varsity Baseball coach. The Celina Middle School staff is thrilled to have Mr. Mikesell as their new leader. He is giving his all for Celina City Schools. We thank him for his excellent baseball coaching years as "one of the area‚Äôs best"! #CelinaNowBulldogForever #MrAndyMikesell #DoWhatsExpected #AndThenDoSomeMore

post_text: We would like to recognize Mrs. Sandy Stammen, Head Start Education Manager on #NationalPrincipalsDay today. Mrs. Stammen leads the educational part of the Head Start program and has been serving in the Celina City Schools district for the past 4 years. With the turnover in staff and the added and changed Head Start classrooms, Mrs. Stammen thrives in the opportunity to lead the staff with new curriculum advances and classroom innovations! Mrs. Stammen is one of those who keeps a positive outlook on every situation. This attitude allows her to lead her staff in accomplishing tasks some might view as previously being unattainable. #CelinaNowBulldogForever #MercerCountyHeadStart

Today is #NationalPrincipalsDay as we recognize Mr. Tim Buschur, Tri Star Director and Mr. Brian Stetler, Tri Star Assistant Director.
Mr. Buschur has been serving in the Celina City Schools district for 22 years and "Career Tech" is his middle name. Mr. Buschur can share so much of the history of the Tri Star program. His work with the local industries has helped Tri Star to reach new levels in enrollment and student success.
Mr. Stetler has been serving the district also for 22 years and is the unsung hero at Tri Star. He does so much of the behind-the-scenes work. So many of the teachers at Tri Star have improved their trade due to Mr. Stetler‚Äôs involvement! Thank you, Gentlemen for your dedication to our students and the Tri Star Programs. #TriStarCareerCompact #CelinaNowBulldogForever #MrTimBuschur #MrBrianStetler

shared_text:
Celina High School
April 29 at 3:00 PM ¬∑

Class of 2020,

Herff Jones will be here THIS SATURDAY, May 2, 2020, from 9:00 AM until 12:00 PM, to distribute Caps, Gowns, Tassels, Honor Cords, and Sashes. This will be a curbside pickup so all you need to do is pull up in front of the high school, give us your name, and receive your items. In order to expedite the process we would like for you to arrive according to the following schedule:

Last names - Adams - Gump from 9:00AM - 10:00 AM

Last names - Haines - Noll from 10:00 AM - 11:00 AM

Last names - Orick - Yenser from 11:00 AM - 12:00 PM

If you are unable to make your scheduled time, you may come during one of the other time slots. If you are unable to pick up your items on this date, please email Mr. Metz (Phil.Metz@celinaschools.org) to make other arrangements.

* Note: Graduation items will only be released to the student or family member! Do not ask your friends to pick up your cap and gown.

** Note: Diplomas will NOT be issued at this time. We are still waiting for the possibility of a modified Graduation Ceremony.

Looking forward to seeing you on Saturday! üíö

** Note: Diplomas will NOT be issued at this time. We are still waiting for the possibility of a modified Graduation Ceremony.

Looking forward to seeing you on Saturday! üíö

"Ann Esselstein scholarship information--We are planning to award 1 scholarship each to a graduating senior from Celina and Parkway. We would like to fully endow each in Annie's memory as continuing education was near and dear to her heart! Please make checks out to: Mercer County Civic Foundation, PO Box 439, Celina, OH 45822. Put "Esselstein Scholarship" on the memo line on the check. Please share with your friends so we can make this happen! God bless you all!"

You may also donate via this link.

shared_text:
CHS Spring Musical
March 30 at 7:38 PM ¬∑

It is with a heavy heart that I announce our Spring Musical production of ‚ÄúHow to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying‚Äù is now officially cancelled. Thank you to all of my wonderful cast and crew for all of your hard work. You made me so proud of all you accomplished!

Seniors- you are so special to me and we have made so many wonderful memories that can never be taken from us! From the very first show you did with me as 7th graders - Flat Stanley Jr., to Lion King Jr. then Little Shop of Horrors, Willy Wonka, Newsies to How To Succeed in Business Without Really Trying - you were an amazing group! It was a privilege to work with you and create with you in the musicals and plays! You have more than made your mark on our Celina Theatre program and you will forever be in my heart

post_text:
The administration of Celina City Schools is saddened to share that we have lost one of our own. Middle School Principal, Ann Esselstein, has left an extremely positive impact on so many of us over her 23 years of service to the Celina community. Ann continued to inspire us to ‚ÄúDo what is expected, and then do some more!‚Äù. Under her dedicated leadership, Celina Middle School students raised over $250,000 for cancer research.

Given that we are all dealing with a national emergency, and are not able to do the things that we normally would do as a part of our grieving process, we are sharing the attached documents/images which may help you and/or your children.

Students may write a note to the Esselstein family and share these notes with their teachers, so that we are able to forward these notes to the family. You may also send these notes to our Middle school counselor or assistant principal at amy.spriggs@celinaschools.org or andy.mikesell@celinaschools.org

Thank you for your kind thoughts and prayers,
Dr. Ken Schmiesing

Tri Star Career Compact
March 12 at 2:35 PM ¬∑

Tri Star CBI students in Celina were treated to a 4-part series on career opportunities in Public Service/Safety over the past several weeks. Sheriff Jeff Grey kicked things off on Jan. 8, followed by WSU-LC Police Academy Commander Mark Ernst on Jan. 23, Celina Police Chief Tom Wale and Fire Chief Doug Wolters on March 5, and St. Marys Firefighter/Paramedic Matt Schrolucke on March 12. All gave fantastic presentations and stressed the immediate need for employees in these areas/departments. A huge thank you to all 5 of these gentleman for your time and your commitment to our communities!

Ohio FBLA
February 18 at 6:24 PM ¬∑

Get to know your State Historian. Kobey Simpson is a junior at Celina High School. Kobey serves as the Ohio FBLA State Historian for the 2019-2020 year. As an FBLA state officer, Kobey is learning the endless possibilities FBLA has to offer and how it can impact him and other fellow members. Kobey is learning more about his state officer team and building a strong bond with them to become closer as friends and workmates. Kobey currently job shadows Accountants, CEO‚Äôs, and Financial Managers to get experience in the booming business world. Kobey is fully dedicated to the complete experience of FBLA and expanding your World of Opportunity both in the classroom and in the expanding business economy. Leadership to Kobey is that a leader must know themselves before getting to know others, no one follows a stranger.

Ohio FBLA
February 13 at 2:53 PM ¬∑

Get to know your State Central Region Vice President. Gaven Nash is excited to be serving as your 2019-2020 Ohio Future Business Leaders of America Central Vice President for the second year in a row. He is currently a senior at Celina. Being in FBLA since his freshman year and becoming a national qualifier illustrates his potential to be a state officer. Other than being in FBLA, Gaven is currently class president while being on the varsity football and wrestling team at his school and he has also participated in student council and marching band. This year, Gaven is hoping to introduce all members to world of opportunities with Ohio FBLA. Leadership to Gaven is a quality that someone has where they always do what‚Äôs right in certain situations.

Tri Star Career Compact
January 30 at 11:39 AM ¬∑

A huge thanks to Gentlemen's Quarters owner (and former Tri Star student) Brian Moeller for speaking to Tri Star CBI students in Celina today about the barber industry! According to Brian, there is a real need for barbers in Ohio, with about 1 barber for every 668 men in the state according to the lastest census. The last remaining "full time" barbershop in Celina, there were 5 "full time" barbers when Brian started his business 10 years ago!

Celina Primary School
January 27 at 3:07 PM ¬∑

We continue to have children out with a variety of illnesses (influenza A & B, Strep Throat... to name a few).

If your child has a fever, even a low grade, please respect the 24-hour policy. Children must be fever-free, without medication, for 24 hours before returning to school. (Even if they say they feel ok.... remember fever-free.)

We are doing our best to try to keep all our kids (and staff) healthy and prevent the spread of these illnesses! Please help us out.

shared_text:
Jason King
January 19 at 1:34 PM ¬∑

Jaden‚Äôs first opponent in this weekend‚Äôs tournament was a young man with Down‚Äôs Syndrome. Once he saw who he was wrestling he knew what to do.

They exchanged takedowns and wrestled for 3 minutes. The smiles on the face of his opponent says it all! Everyone cheered for this young man so loudly...it was great!

When he came to shake my hand after the match I told him, ‚ÄúYou did great on those takedowns you got!‚Äù
With an ear to ear grin on his face he beamed with joy and said ‚ÄúTHANKS!!‚Äù

I know any one of our Celina Wrestlers would have done the same. Jaden was the fortunate one that got to represent his team and prove that a Champion is more than just a person who wins a match!

I love this sport!!!

(Music by Switchfoot. ‚ÄúLive It Well.‚Äù)

Sixth Grade Parents (who are interested) only:
The College Credit Plus program allows college ready students in grades 7-12 to enroll in college courses
while still in high school. The program allows students to earn dual credit at both the college and the
high school. Students interested in participating in the program for the 2020-2021 school year must
attend a mandatory informational meeting on Wednesday, Jan. 22 nd . The meeting will be at 6:30 p.m. in
the high school lecture hall. If you would like more information please speak with guidance office at the high school.

shared_text:
Celina Middle School added 7 new photos.
December 21, 2019 at 12:06 PM ¬∑

Check out this FANTASTIC project Mrs. Guggenbiller and Mr. Gudorf's students recently completed! Below you will find a description of the project.
THANK YOU WALMART!!!

Students began the project by taking measurements of the varsity soccer dugouts using tape measures donated by Walmart (they donated $85 worth of tape measures). Students were then placed into groups and assigned a section of the dugout. Next, students scaled their measurements down and began sketching their models using a program called SketchUp on their Chromebooks. Once students made a 3D model of their structure, they were grouped again so that each student had a different piece of the dugout. Next, students compiled each structure of the dugout and then sent them on to the 3D printer. Models are roughly 5 inches and each takes roughly 2 hours to print on CMS's 3D printer. Once printed, students build them like model airplanes.

#bettertogether #cmsbulldogs #dowhatsexpected #andthendosomemore #wearefamily #learnandgrow #stem #thankyouwalmart

Celina Primary School
December 4, 2019 at 9:40 AM ¬∑

Just a reminder:

Celina Primary School will be participating in a coat/winter clothing drive called Santa‚Äôs Helpers: Coats For Christmas. This coat drive is run by a group of students from Celina High School as a way to get more involved in the community and provide children with the necessary supplies they need for the cold weather.

Donations may be dropped off at the Celina Primary School office from now until December 13th. We will be accepting gently used or new donations. If you have any gloves, hats, coats, scarves, or socks lying around at home, please feel free to donate them. All of the items donated must be for children from grades K-2. We encourage you to please spread the word and donate if possible!

If you have any questions or concerns, please feel free to contact santashelperscfc@gmail.com. We are so excited to see the outcome of this coat drive and we hope you are too! Help us to spread love and joy within our community this holiday season! #CPSLoveLeadInspire #CelinaNowBulldogForever

This coat drive is run by a group of students from Celina High School as a way to get more involved in the community and provide children with the necessary supplies they need for the cold weather.

Donations may be dropped off at the Celina Primary School office from now until December 13th. We will be accepting gently used or new donations. If you have any gloves, hats, coats, scarves, or socks lying around at home, please feel free to donate them. All of the items donated must be for children from grades K-2. We encourage you to please spread the word and donate if possible!

If you have any questions or concerns, please feel free to contact santashelperscfc@gmail.com. We are so excited to see the outcome of this coat drive and we hope you are too! Help us to spread love and joy within our community this holiday season! #CPSLoveLeadInspire #CelinaNowBulldogForever

Celina Primary School
November 27, 2019 at 11:22 AM ¬∑

On Friday, Mrs. Smith's class participated in a lesson that tied in three subjects: social studies, writing, and science! The students learned how to make butter in a jar, comparing the process to churning butter like many people did in the past. Next, they wrote How-To stories, detailing step-by-step on what to do. They discovered the cream went from a liquid to a solid as it formed into butter. It was an integrated lesson that ended with yummy, buttery, cinnamon toast! #CPSLoveLeadInspire #LearningisFunandTasty #MrsAshleySmith

Last week, Mrs. Link's 3rd grade class (with the help of Mrs. Goettemoeller) at Celina Elementary School were presented $200 in Amazon gift cards to purchase wobble stools for their classroom! They were the overall Mercer County winner of the Red Ribbon Week Photo Contest! See the picture for them with their new items for the classroom!

The theme this year was..."SEND A MESSAGE. STAY DRUG FREE!!!"

Prizes are sponsored by the Mercer County Prevention Coalition and Mercer County Elks Golf Club

The Red Ribbon Campaign¬Æ was started when drug traffickers in Mexico City murdered DEA agent Kiki Camarena in 1985. This began the continuing tradition of displaying Red Ribbons as a symbol of intolerance towards the use of drugs.

Celina Primary School
November 7, 2019 at 11:35 AM ¬∑

CPS Families! It's getting cold outside!!!! A couple of reminders from our staff. Please make sure your kids are dressed warmly (and appropriately) for the weather.

We do go outside for recess, so they will need coats, hats, mittens, scarves, etc.

Please make sure your child's coat has a zipper that works. (We found a couple today that did not work.)

Make sure your child's coat has their name inside it. Many times, kids have matching coats and they sometimes get confused.

IF YOU ARE HAVING TROUBLE GETTING A COAT, HAT, GLOVES, ETC. FOR YOUR CHILD AND WOULD LIKE ASSISTANCE. PLEASE PM US ON THIS PAGE OR EMAIL MRS. DUNCAN AND SHE WILL HELP YOU OUT! michelle.duncan@celinaschools.org

#CPSLoveLeadInspire #WelcomeToWinter #OhioWeather #LayersAreGood

Tri Star Career Compact
November 6, 2019 at 1:15 PM ¬∑

Tri Star CBI students in Celina were treated to a wonderful presentation (and delicious cookies) from Grace Goings and Nathan Dicus from Celina Aluminum Precision Technology,
(CAPT). Grace informed students about CAPT's unique Career Interest Program for 18 year old high school students as well as the excellent pay and benefits at CAPT, and Nathan shared his story of career advancement through a willingness to work, good attendance, and available company-paid trainings through CAPT. Thank you Grace and Nathan! Fun fact: CAPT employed 3 high school students last school year. One of these students received a 20 under 20 award for career development, and another entered CAPT's Equipment Service Training Program where he is receiving full tuition paid by CAPT while also being paid to work AND attend classes!

November 6, 2019 at 12:56 PM ¬∑

Congratulations to Celina Middle School ...Mrs. Christie Binkley's class was chosen as the Celina Middle School Winner of the Mercer County Red Ribbon Week Photo Contest!

The theme this year was..."SEND A MESSAGE. STAY DRUG FREE!!!"

The class will be using the $50 award will be used towards a pizza party for her students. Prizes are sponsored by the Mercer County Prevention Coalition and Mercer County Elks Golf Club.

The Red Ribbon Campaign¬Æ was started when drug traffickers in Mexico City murdered DEA agent Kiki Camarena in 1985. This began the continuing tradition of displaying Red Ribbons as a symbol of intolerance towards the use of drugs.
Celina Schools

Mrs. Smith‚Äôs first graders observed the characteristics of worms last week during a science lesson. After many squeals and runaway worms, the class decided that earthworms are living creatures and gummy worms are non-living. At the end of the day, the earthworms were returned back to their home. The gummy worms, however, were never seen again.#CPSLoveLeadInspire #WhereAreTheWorms #ScienceIsFun
